<sn><md>### What is `git blame`? {.text-center}

`git blame` is a command that shows the commit information (author, commit hash, timestamp) for each line in a file.
It helps you:

* Identify the author of a specific line of code.
* Understand when and why a line was changed.
* Trace back to the commit message for context.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Basic Usage{.text-center}

```bash
git blame filename
# with email
git blame -e filename
```

Example:

```bash
git blame app.js
```

This will output each line of the file along with commit hash, author, and timestamp.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Useful Options with `git blame` {.text-center}

#### Show commit summary with author

```bash
git blame -c filename
```

#### Ignore whitespace changes

```bash
git blame -w filename
```

(Useful when lines only shifted due to indentation.)

#### Limit to a range of lines

```bash
git blame -L 10,20 filename
```

Shows blame info only for lines 10 to 20.

#### Show commit hash abbreviation

```bash
git blame --abbrev=8 filename
```</md></sn><sn><md>### Example Output{.text-center}

```bash
5a1fe0d (Alice 2025-09-16 20:14:22 +0600  1) function add(a, b) {
5a1fe0d (Alice 2025-09-16 20:14:22 +0600  2)     return a + b;
839814d (Bob   2025-09-17 12:30:11 +0600  3) }
```

Here:

* Line 1 and 2 were last modified by Alice in commit `5a1fe0d`.
* Line 3 was modified by Bob in commit `839814d`.
</md></sn><sn><md>### Linking Blame to Commit History{.text-center}

Each commit hash from blame output can be investigated:

```bash
git show commit_hash
```

This reveals the full commit message and changes, giving deeper context for why the line was modified.</md></sn><sn><md>### Caution When Using Blame{.text-center}

* **Context matters**: A line may have been copy-pasted or reformatted later. The original idea could come from an earlier commit.
* **Refactoring can mislead**: Blame tracks line history, so if code is reorganized, the "blame" may point to the refactorer, not the original author.
* Use blame as a **collaboration tool**, not to assign faultâ€”its purpose is understanding, not criticism.</md></sn><sn><md>### Summary{.text-center}

* `git blame` shows **who changed each line** and **when**.
* Options like `-L`, `-w`, and `--abbrev` refine the output.
* Combine with `git show` to read commit details.
* Best used for learning context and debugging history, not blaming people.</md></sn><sn><md>### Practise{.text-center}

